at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors","Noradrenaline and dopamine reuptake inhibitor","Monoamine oxidase inhibitor","Nicotinic acetylcholine receptor antagonist","Partial agonist at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVarenicline works as a \u003Cstrong\u003Epartial agonist at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. This mechanism partially stimulates the receptors to reduce symptoms of withdrawal whilst simultaneously preventing nicotine from fully stimulating these receptors if smoking does occur, subsequently reducing the reinforcing effects of continued tobacco use. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike nicotine replacement therapy, varenicline is not a \u003Cstrong\u003Efull agonist\u003C/strong\u003E at \u003Cstrong\u003Enicotinic acetylcholine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt also does not function as a \u003Cstrong\u003Enoradrenaline and dopamine reuptake inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the mechanism of bupropion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVarenicline also does not act as a \u003Cstrong\u003Emonoamine oxidase inhibitor, \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich is the mechanism of monoamine oxidase (MAO) inhibitors used in the treatment of depressive disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPure \u003Cstrong\u003Enicotinic acetylcholine receptor antagonists\u003C/strong\u003E would exacerbate withdrawal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Varenicline functions as a partial agonist at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, helping reduce tobacco cravings while antagonising the positive effect of nicotine.","Nicotine replacement provides measured nicotine doses to ease withdrawal symptoms during smoking cessation.","Bupropion works by blocking noradrenaline and dopamine reuptake while antagonising nicotinic receptors."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43769"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14739"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43769"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-31T09:33:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:33:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7432"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58329"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji